      "markdown": "chronic diseases [3,6]. With advances in neonatal intensive care leading to improved CDH survival, there has been a concomitant shift of clinical focus towards improving CDH survivor morbidity [1].\n\nStructured, long-term surveillance is critical for the early identification and mitigation of CDH morbidity. This is especially true for patients with neurodevelopmental impairment (NDI) [4,[7], [8], [9]. Indeed, up to two-thirds of CDH infants experience some form of neurodevelopmental or psychomotor delay by 3 years of age, which can significantly impact quality of life [2,[10], [11], [12]. NDI is most common in CDH infants requiring respiratory support or oxygen supplementation at day of life 28, in ECLS survivors, in those patients requiring patch repair (i.e. large defects), and in those born prematurely [1,13,14]. Despite recognizing the importance of long-term health surveillance, very few studies have evaluated the impact of survivor morbidity on both the patient and the family [15], [16], [17]. Furthermore, critical assessment of the efficacy of current long-term health surveillance programs in mitigating CDH morbidity and supporting families along their illness journey, or their satisfaction with the services they receive, is lacking.\n\nThe overall objective of this study was to describe the clinical trajectory of patients with CDH and NDI (CDH-NDI) and to explore the lived experience of families and their satisfaction with existing support resources. Understanding the clinical trajectory of patients allows us to identify inflections in care, periods of increased stress or concern with respect to the child's health and the impact on the family. Furthermore, knowledge of family satisfaction with supportive resources has important implications for quality improvement, resource allocation and healthcare delivery. We hypothesized that CDH children with severe NDI and their families would have higher unmet needs compared to CDH children without NDI, over the trajectory of their illness.\n\n## 2. Methods\n\nWe conducted a single-center cohort study of CDH patients with NDI followed in the long-term health surveillance clinic at the Montreal Children's Hospital (MCH). We previously identified 27 patients with NDI who formed the basis of this study [18].\n\n### 2.1. Determination of NDI\n\nThe entire CDH health surveillance cohort was first screened for NDI risk using classical clinical criteria, which included the need for extracorporeal life support (ECLS), oxygen supplementation at 28 days of life, and requirement for patch repair of their diaphragmatic defect (i.e. larger defect sizes) [1,13,14]. This was followed by the novel application of the CDH Study Group Mortality prediction score as an additional screen [19], which categorizes patients into low, moderate and high risk of mortality based on Apgar scores, birthweight, presence of pulmonary hypertension, and cardiac or chromosomal anomalies [20]. The following cut-offs were used for categorizing patients into low (0), moderate (1-2) or high (>3) risk of mortality, and were based off of the articles by Brindle et al. [19], and Cochius-den Otter et al [20]. NDI was subsequently confirmed in the entire cohort by formal developmental pediatrician assessments at 18 and 36 months, and correlated with the Bayley-3 assessment, when available [18]. The two-phase screening process demonstrated high fidelity in identifying the entire NDI cohort, with the developmental pediatrician assessment as the gold standard. Patients were classified as mild, moderate, and severe NDI based on developmental pediatrician assessment.\n\n### 2.2. Phase 1: Evaluation of clinical variables\n\nPhase 1 of the study involved retrospective review of prospectively collected clinical data and an assessment of outpatient clinic usage data for CDH patients with and without NDI. Patient recruitment occurred during neonatal admission or subsequent follow-up clinic appointments, when patients were consented and enrolled in our REDCap data registry. Data was collected prospectively from birth and retrospectively analyzed from March 2023 to February 2024. Patient demographics were obtained from the REDCap database, as well as from the electronic medical record (EMR). Clinic usage data was primarily obtained from detailed prospective patient summaries maintained by our clinic nurse specialist, comprised of hospital visits, telephone logs to the clinic nurse specialist, as well as correspondence and visit records with outside practitioners. The visits recorded in the patient summaries were cross-referenced with the EMR and the REDCap database. Clinic usage data for the non-NDI cohort was obtained as a comparison group. All visits beginning from initial hospital discharge until the end of data collection (February 2024) were included. Patients were excluded if they were less than 2 years of age at the time of study data analysis (February 2024), if they were diagnosed with CDH beyond 2 years of life, if they did not receive surgery for their CDH, if they were not actively followed in the clinic beyond 1 year of life, and/or if they had a significant chromosomal anomaly or a congenital heart defect requiring cardiac surgery. Visits to the clinic were categorized as \"scheduled\" if they followed the prescribed follow-up frequency at 4, 9, 18, and 36 months of age and every 2 years thereafter, which was based on the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) CDH post-discharge follow-up recommendations [21]. Visits were also considered as \"scheduled\" when patients were assessed by two or more CDH clinic members (e.g. surgery, respirology, neonatology, gastroenterology and cardiology) within 7 days, to account for older patients who were seen before the introduction of the multidisciplinary clinic in 2012. \"Unscheduled\" visits were visits that fell outside of the prescribed visit pattern and were further sub-classified by specialty.\n\n### 2.3. Phase 2: satisfaction with existing hospital resources\n\nPhase 2 involved a survey to assess family satisfaction with existing hospital resources (Appendix A). Data was collected from March 2023 to February 2024. The survey, comprised of a 5-point Likert scale and free text boxes, assessed satisfaction with known transition points in care, including the neonatal intensive care unit (NICU), ward, discharge, and first clinic appointment. Following REB requirements, a member of the existing clinical team (clinic nurse) invited all eligible CDH-NDI families actively followed in the health surveillance clinic to participate. Interested families were then sent a digital copy of the survey by email. Participation in the survey was voluntary and participation implied consent. The survey was offered digitally in both English and French, with results tabulated together. Any French comments were translated to English by a bilingual member of the research team.\n\n### 2.4. Data extraction and analysis\n\nPatient demographic and clinical information was extracted from the CDH longterm follow-up clinic REDCap data registry and EMR. Patient clinic usage data was extracted from their clinical summaries, the REDCap data registry, and the EMR. Results are presented as means with standard deviation (SD) or median with interquartile range (IQR) for continuous variables and counts with proportions for categorical variables. Categorical variables were analyzed with Fisher's exact test. The ANOVA test and Kruskal-Wallis test were"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "used for continuous variables with parametric or non-parametric distributions, respectively. Statistical analyses were performed using Rstudio (Version 2023.12.1 + 402, International open-source collaborative). The English and French survey results were combined and subsequently tabulated for each Likert category. The 5-point Likert rating was converted to: 'Agree' = 4, 'Somewhat Agree' = 3, 'Somewhat Disagree' = 2, 'Disagree' = 1. 'Not Applicable/Unknown' was treated as missing data, with the subsequent number of responses for that particular question being reduced by 1 . Results are presented as means with standard deviation for each question, as well as counts of 'Agree' and proportions.\n\n### 2.5. Ethical considerations\n\nThe study received research ethics board approval (REB 2023-8964). Informed consent was obtained prior to prospective data collection in our REDCap Clinic Database (Phase 1 data), and was implied for survey participation in the study (Phase 2 data), as is typical for this form of data collection. Results were anonymized to ensure patient confidentiality.\n\n## 3. Results\n\n### 3.1. Phase 1: retrospective chart review\n\nOf 122 patients who are included in our long-term surveillance database, 27 patients were previously identified as having NDI, and were included in this study [18]. Of these, 2 patients were identified as having mild NDI, 7 moderate NDI, and 18 severe NDI based on 18- and 36-month screening by our CDH clinic developmental pediatrician. All 27 patients met inclusion criteria. Of the 95 nonNDI patients followed in our clinic, 31 were excluded due to age at time of study (8), death before age 2 (1), no follow-up in our clinic beyond age 1 (14), no surgery (1, possible diaphragmatic eventration), major chromosomal anomalies (2), and diagnosis past age 2 (5). The final sample included 64 CDH patients without NDI. Patient demographic variables and outcomes are presented in Table 1.\n\nThere was no difference in the rates of prenatal diagnosis, gestational age at birth, birthweight, delivery method, or CDH\nlaterality among groups. The severe NDI cohort was more likely to have a lower Apgar score at 5 min of life ( $\\mathrm{p}=0017$ ), a greater need for inhaled nitric oxide (iNO) ( $\\mathrm{p}<0.001$ ), a longer duration of ventilation ( $\\mathrm{p}<0.001$ ) and a greater length of both ICU ( $\\mathrm{p}<0.001$ ) and overall hospital stay ( $\\mathrm{p}<0.001$ ), when compared to the mild/ moderate NDI and non-NDI cohorts. When comparing the clinical support required at discharge, the groups had similar rates of oxygen supplementation and enteral access. Additionally, the severe NDI cohort was more likely to have gastroesophageal reflux (GERD) ( $\\mathrm{p}=0.002$ ), with a rate more than double that of the other groups.\n\nClinic usage data are presented in Fig. 1 as the median number of scheduled and unscheduled visits per patient between the 3 groups. While the greatest number of visits per patient (both scheduled and unscheduled) was observed in the first 4 years of life amongst all groups, the non-NDI cohort required fewer total visits compared to both the mild/moderate and severe NDI cohorts. Despite the differences in clinical demographic variables observed between the NDI cohorts, the median numbers of total visits were similar in the first two years of life. However, the severe NDI cohort required many more unscheduled visits when compared to the other groups. This difference was particularly notable in the first 2 years of life, but remained significant until 4 years of age (Table 2). A breakdown of the categories of the unscheduled visits in the first four years of life is presented in Fig. 2, with the severe NDI cohort requiring more emergency department, medical specialist (i.e. ENT, gastroenterology, respirology), and ancillary (i.e. audiology, nutrition, physical and occupational therapy) visits than the other cohorts.\n\n### 3.2. Phase 2: satisfaction survey\n\nAll 27 patients with NDI followed in our long-term follow-up clinic were approached to participate in the satisfaction survey. After a total of four communications (an initial correspondence, and three reminder e-mails), with links to both the English and French surveys online, the final sample included 12 families who participated in the survey. Survey results are presented in Table 3. Parents were extremely satisfied with the initial diagnosis and hospitalization in the NICU, with comments such as \"great follow-up, great\n\nTable 1\nParticipant demographics.\n\n|  | Severe <br> NDI (n = 18) | Mild \\& Moderate <br> NDI (n = 9) | CDH without <br> NDI (n = 64) | p-value |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| Demographic and Birth Details |  |  |  |  |\n| Male | 12 (67) | 4 (44) | 36 (56) | 0.528 |\n| Prenatal Diagnosis | 13 (72) | 4 (44) | 33 (52) | 0.213 |\n| Gestational Age at Birth (weeks) | 38.2 (2.0) | 39.0 (0.8) | 38.9 (1.97) | 0.266 |\n| Birth weight (kg) | 2.99 (0.6) | 3.12 (0.5) | 3.17 (0.5) | 0.613 |\n| Apgar at 5 min | $6(5-7)$ | $8(7-9)$ | $8(6-9)$ | 0.017 |\n| C-section | 2 (11) | 2 (22) | 18 (28) | 0.383 |\n| Hospital Course |  |  |  |  |\n| Length of ICU Stay (days) | 34 (22-55) | 7.5 (2-10) | 18 (10-40) | $<0.001$ |\n| Length of Hospital Stay (days) | 41 (35-72) | 10 (5-14) | 22 (14-46) | $<0.001$ |\n| Need for iNO | 13 (72) | 0 (0) | 24 (38) | $<0.001$ |\n| Duration of Ventilation (days) | 16 (9-25) | 3 (1-5) | $8(3-12)$ | $<0.001$ |\n| CDH Details |  |  |  |  |\n| Left-sided CDH | 13 (72) | 9 (100) | 51 (80) | 0.278 |\n| Requirement for Patch repair | 9 (50) | 0 (0) | 12 (19) | 0.005 |\n| Post-hospital Discharge |  |  |  |  |\n| Oxygen Support on Discharge | 3 (17) | 0 (0) | 5 (8) | 0.513 |\n| GERD on Discharge | 16 (89) | 4 (44) | 28 (44) | 0.002 |\n| Enteral Access on Discharge | 6 (33) | 1 (11) | 16 (25) | 0.499 |\n| Pneumonia in 1st Year of Life | 4 (22) | 1 (11) | 12 (19) | 0.832 |\n\nValues expressed in count (S), or median (int