 failures in communication:\n\"The medical follow-up didn't give us the impression that the situation was fully understood and well managed. We always received the comment that the medical team was in an observation phase throughout our 3-week stay.\"\n\nSatisfaction with the period between hospital discharge and the first clinic visit was also high, with all families indicating knowledge of how to contact the CDH care team, and satisfaction with this communication process. Once again, while satisfaction was generally high with the first clinic visit, many parents expressed dissatisfaction with their ability to communicate with other parents of CDH children. Additionally, some parents expressed dissatisfaction with the wait time between clinicians and communication surrounding investigations being performed. General comments provided at the end of the survey suggested that despite areas for improvement, parents were overall satisfied with the care their child received, and the format of the long-term follow-up clinic:\n\"We were very satisfied with the care of our child. It was only during the extended care stay that we felt left to ourselves and that the professionals didn't know how to approach our child's case.\""
