      "markdown": "\"The CDH team has been professional, compassionate, helpful, knowledgeable and coordinated within themselves and the hospital from the moment of diagnosis until the latest follow up. A huge thank you to everyone!\"\n\n## 4. Discussion\n\nTo date, there is limited literature exploring the impact of associated co-morbidities on the quality of life of CDH patients and their families. The inclusion of family experiences offers new opportunities for quality improvement, particularly in vulnerable populations like CDH. Our findings provide evidence that CDH patients with severe NDI require increased support in the first years of life when compared to patients without NDI or those with mild/moderate NDI. Specifically, the severe NDI cohort required many more unscheduled visits, suggesting the need for increased surveillance efforts outside those recommended by the AAP [21] and advocated for in clinical practice guidelines [1,22]. Importantly, the unscheduled visits were often by health professionals outside of pediatric surgery and in particular, the emergency department. Patients most often required additional visits relating to feeding (i.e. failure to thrive, severe GERD) and respiratory (i.e. asthma and frequent respiratory infections) difficulties. These findings underscore the vital importance of a truly inter-disciplinary CDH health surveillance team that can provide access to other health professionals quickly on an \"as needed\" basis. Unfortunately, substantial variability continues to exist with regards to long-term health surveillance team composition, surveillance time points, surveillance duration and the diagnostic tests offered [4,7,23-25]. While our institution offers structured follow-up with a pediatric surgeon, respirologist, neonatologist, cardiologist, developmental pediatrician and gastroenterologist (when required), with follow-up points based on the AAP timeline, our results indicate that more intensive health surveillance and greater resources are required for the severe NDI cohort in the first years of life. Further analysis of the unmet needs in the severe NDI cohort is needed to ensure patients and families are supported appropriately. Our ability to anticipate these increased needs, and structure our surveillance programs around these \"inflection points\" in care, should lead to less resource utilization and unscheduled visits, especially in the severe NDI cohort [18,25,26]. This strategy may be particularly useful in resource-limited settings in which patients could be risk stratified to allow the limited, available support to be directed to patients in the highest-risk category [26]. Perhaps most importantly, our families, as well as other patient advocacy groups have identified the \"life journey\" as an important issue for clinicians to understand [27].\n\nThe results of our satisfaction survey suggest that parents are satisfied with the resources provided within our institution, particularly with the 'one-stop shop' offered by the long-term health surveillance clinic. Despite this, however, areas for improvement remain. In particular, survey results indicated dissatisfaction with communication amongst medical teams, particularly during transfer from NICU to ward. These results are not surprising, since patient transfer requires coordinated verbal transition of care amongst providers as well as the physical relocation of the patient, which if done sub-optimally, increases the risks of patient complication [28-30]. The risk of error is further exacerbated in pediatric surgical patients, due to the multidisciplinary coordination required, which can result in misunderstandings due to differing knowledge backgrounds, role ambiguity, differences in values, lack of teamwork and poor communication [29]. Furthermore, the added element of parental anxiety can further complicate the patient transfer event [28]. A\nrecent single-institution observational study of 31 post-surgical pediatric patient handovers demonstrated significant disagreements between teamwork ratings of transferring and receiving teams [31]. This study involved 109 ratings of involved providers, with the handoff team demonstrating situational awareness that was statistically greater than the receiving team [31]. While research on best handover practices is sparse, structured protocols, face-to-face transfer events with minimized disruptions, and common language to minimize errors and increase awareness and understanding among the receiving team have been suggested [29,30,32]. Quality improvement initiatives should consider a protocolized transfer process for CDH patients from NICU to ward, to ensure all teams have adequate situational awareness, and that communication and expectations amongst providers and with parents is improved. Design of these initiatives should consider barriers to implementation, such as time constraints limiting face-to-face transfer and knowledge gaps between transferring providers. Engaging key stakeholders in the design of these initiatives will ensure relevancy to those involved in the process, and will aid in overcoming implementation barriers.\n\nAnother common theme to emerge in the survey was a strong desire to interact with other families of children with CDH. The sentiments expressed by the parents in our study were echoed in a study of the needs of parents during prenatal counseling for CDH [33]. In this qualitative study of 19 families who had children with moderate or severe pulmonary hypoplasia, parents expressed feeling isolated, as they did not know anyone else in a similar situation [33]. Peer support organizations were considered helpful in providing parents information about living with a child with CDH, however this was not uniformly available to all parents. In our study, parents found the online support provided by advocacy groups to be lacking, and instead desired face-to-face tangible support from families in the same local context. This finding is in contrast with a recent qualitative study of parents' experiences with CDH child care, which identified online support forums, such as Facebook, to be helpful in managing insecurities and providing reassurance [34]. It is possible that local context may play a role in the desired type of support (online vs. face-to-face). This theme will be further explored in future focus groups with parents and their children to advise future quality improvement initiatives such as the development of a formal support group, or an informal support network.\n\nOur study has many strengths, including a patient-centered approach, longitudinal assessment of health visits stratified by NDI severity, and the assessment of satisfaction with hospital-provided resources. There are however some significant limitations as well. The visit data may not represent all unscheduled visits for a patient, particularly if visits were outside of our hospital network, and therefore not captured in our EMR. To overcome this challenge, we cross-referenced the EMR with patient clinical summaries maintained by our clinic nurse. Still, despite our best efforts, it is possible some visits may have been missed if no record was sent to our clinic nurse. It is therefore possible that our visit data may underestimate the true number of unscheduled visits for patients with CDH, which further demonstrates the importance of a multi-disciplinary CDH clinic to reduce these unscheduled visits, especially for those patients with severe NDI. A second limitation relates to the specific healthcare system of our study which may hinder generalizability of our results. Our long-term follow-up clinic operates in a singlepayer public healthcare system, where patients are not charged for their care, and their access to the clinic is not dependent on insurance status. Private payer systems may note differences in their clinic usage patterns. Despite this challenge, the same clinic usage patterns are likely to be observed in other healthcare systems, if not further exaggerated for patients without access to formal scheduled"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "visits, who will therefore rely on unscheduled visits to providers outside of the formal surveillance clinic structure. Lastly, we must acknowledge the possibility of recall bias present within our satisfaction survey strategy. Our survey asked parents to comment on known transition points in care early in the CDH care trajectory (NICU stay, transition to ward, hospital discharge and first clinic visit). While these are memorable moments not easily forgotten by families, it is possible that parents with older children may have had difficulty remembering these early moments. Given that few studies have evaluated patient and parent satisfaction with support resources, we believe this is a first step in understanding our patient and parent needs. Future studies may wish to collect surveys at different time points with questions tailored to each stage of the CDH care trajectory, to avoid the possibility of recall bias.\n\n## 5. Conclusion\n\nThis study is the first of its kind to assess the clinical trajectory and lived experiences of CDH-NDI children and families during long-term health surveillance. Children with CDH and severe NDI require increased support over the trajectory of their care, particularly in the first 4 years of life, suggesting that more formal visits may be required during this period. Future quality improvement efforts should aim to improve communication amongst medical teams, particularly during the transition from NICU to ward, and increase access to supportive resources, with the consideration of support groups, or other means of communication between families. Inclusion of patients and families in the development of these quality improvement measures will ensure that supportive resources offered are both desired, and effective. While much is known about the ongoing comorbidities associated with CDH, this study reveals there are significant gaps in knowledge with regards to the support needs of both patients and their families. Continued emphasis on the patient and family voice is needed to shed light on the impact of these findings, and to encourage effective resource allocation and patient-centered care for this vulnerable population.\n\n## Funding/support\n\nThis work was funded by the Mirella and Lino Saputo Foundation Chair in Pediatric Surgical Education and Patient and FamilyCentered Care, Department of Pediatric Surgery, McGill University Faculty of Medicine and Health Sciences, the John McCrae Fellowship, McGill University Faculty of Medicine and Health Sciences, the bourse Aude-Gabrielle et McKinley Bich pour l'excellence des soins en santÃ© mentale, McGill University Hospital Centre Research Institute, as well as the Montreal Children's Hospital Foundation.\n\n## Conflict of interest\n\nThe authors have no conflicts of interest relevant to this article to disclose.\n\n## Appendix A. Satisfaction Survey\n\n## Dear parents\n\nIn order to help us provide the best care possible, we would like to seek your feedback on some of the aspects of the care provided to our patients with CDH at our institution.\n\nThank you for helping us make a difference!\n\n| 1. HOSPITALIZATION | Not Applicable/ | Agree | Somewhat Agree | Somewhat Disagree | Disagree |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| -NICU (Neonatal | Unknown |  |  |  |  |\n| Unit(R065) |  |  |  |  |  |\n| The diagnosis of CDH was explained clearly |  |  |  |  |  |\n| The long-term effects of CDH were explained clearly |  |  |  |  |  |\n| The tests required for the follow-up of CDH were explained clearly |  |  |  |  |  |\n| There was good communication amongst medical staff concerning the care of CDH |  |  |  |  |  |\n| The encounter with the primary CDH clinic nurse in the NICU was helpful |  |  |  |  |  |\n| The meeting with another member of the CDH team in the NICU was/ could have been useful |  |  |  |  |  |\n| We felt adequately prepared for our child's discharge and to care for him/her at home |  |  |  |  |  |\n| Do